{# ══ Activity 4 — Target Abstract ════════════════════════════════════ #}

{% call activitySection(4, "Identify Your Target Abstract", "crosshair") %}
<p>
  Before writing your abstract, it is useful to clarify what type you are aiming for. Work through
  the decisions below. If you are uncertain about any dimension, look at published abstracts from
  your target venue for guidance.
</p>
<ol style="color:#ddd; line-height:2.2;">
  <li><strong>Publication type:</strong> Journal article / Conference proceedings / Thesis or dissertation</li>
  <li><strong>Length:</strong> Regular (150–300 words) / Extended (1–4 pages)</li>
  <li><strong>Format:</strong> Traditional (prose) / Structured (headings) / Graphical</li>
  <li><strong>Timing:</strong> Post hoc (research complete) / A priori (research in progress — promissory)</li>
  <li><strong>Audience:</strong> Specialist / Interdisciplinary / General public</li>
  <li><strong>Discipline:</strong> Your specific subfield (e.g., natural language processing, software engineering)</li>
</ol>
<p>
  Once you have worked through these dimensions, you will have a clear picture of the conventions
  you need to follow. The remaining units in this course will help you apply those conventions at
  the level of content, structure, and language.
</p>
{% endcall %}


{# ══ Activity 5 — Getting to Know the Genre ══════════════════════════ #}

{% call activitySection(5, "Getting to Know the Genre", "binoculars") %}
<p>
  The single most effective preparation for writing an abstract is reading a large number of abstracts
  from your target venue. This is called <strong>genre immersion</strong>. As you read, pay attention to:
</p>
<ul style="color:#ddd; line-height:2.2;">
  <li>The typical length of abstracts in that venue</li>
  <li>Which rhetorical moves appear (introduction, purpose, method, results, discussion)</li>
  <li>The order in which moves appear</li>
  <li>The level of technical detail in the method section</li>
  <li>Whether results are quantified with numbers and statistics</li>
  <li>Whether limitations or future work are mentioned</li>
</ul>
<p>
  For conference papers, check the proceedings of the same conference from previous years.
  For journal articles, search recent issues of your target journal. For a thesis, consult your
  university library's repository.
</p>
{% endcall %}


{# ══ Review ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}

{% call reviewSection() %}
<p>Test your recall of the five abstract types. Expand each item to check your understanding.</p>

<div class="accordion mt-3" id="u01-review">
  {% call accordion("rev-u01-a", "Traditional — what is the key feature?") %}
  <p>A continuous prose abstract with no headings, typically 150–250 words. The writer chooses the move sequence. It is the most common type in computer science and related disciplines.</p>
  {% endcall %}
  {% call accordion("rev-u01-b", "Structured — what is the key feature?") %}
  <p>Uses prescribed headings (e.g., Objective, Methods, Results, Conclusion) that may be specified by the journal. It is the default in medicine and health sciences and tends to be longer than a traditional abstract.</p>
  {% endcall %}
  {% call accordion("rev-u01-c", "Graphical — what is the key feature?") %}
  <p>Communicates the research through a visual element (diagram, flowchart, infographic) with minimal text. Common in materials science, chemistry, and biology.</p>
  {% endcall %}
  {% call accordion("rev-u01-d", "Promissory — what is the key feature?") %}
  <p>Describes research that is not yet complete. The results section is replaced by anticipated findings or a promise that results will be shared. Common in humanities and linguistics conferences.</p>
  {% endcall %}
  {% call accordion("rev-u01-e", "Extended — what is the key feature?") %}
  <p>Substantially longer than a standard abstract — typically 2–4 pages. Allows for detailed method description, related work, and preliminary results. Used in some computer science and engineering conference tracks.</p>
  {% endcall %}
</div>

